<Base title="Zero-downtime migration of the power-management model — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">migration</span>
  <h1>Zero-downtime migration of the power-management model</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Moving live plants from a legacy power-management model to a new
    power-plant-controller abstraction — with the data, the calculations, and
    the transition period all accounted for.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    Power control (curtailment setpoints, grid-operator commands) was modeled on
    a legacy device type that had grown into a dead end: the platform needed a
    proper power-plant-controller (PPC) abstraction to support newer plant
    topologies. Hundreds of live systems were writing power-management data
    every interval — there was no maintenance window in which the world stood
    still.
  </p>

  <h2>Design</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>Migration script as a first-class deliverable:</strong> device and
      historical data migrated programmatically, reviewable and re-runnable —
      not a one-off console session.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The transition gap, handled explicitly:</strong> between "new
      device exists" and "old device retired" lies a window where data can land
      on either side. The calculation pipeline was taught to create the PPC
      device on demand and backfill the gap, so no interval went missing during
      cutover.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A clean cutover of side effects:</strong> setpoint-event
      calculation was switched off for the legacy device exactly when the PPC
      took over — no double-calculation, no silent stop.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Impact</h2>
  <p>
    The fleet moved to the new model with no data loss and no downtime. The
    abstraction paid for itself a year later: introducing <strong>virtual
    PPCs</strong> (for plants whose controller is implicit) was a schema design,
    one new calculation module, and a set of API endpoints — an extension, not
    another migration.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    In an online migration the interesting artifact isn't the script — it's the
    inventory of everything that reads or writes the old model, and a decision
    for each one about what happens <em>during</em> the transition, not just
    after it. The gap window is the design surface.
  </p>
</Base>
